I was so sure I tested this, but after our call did another reproducer and it's clear that, when you add rules with the same path, that match `HEAD` methods _before_ the rule for `GET` methods, then it works as expected. if you reverse the order of the `add_route_endpoint` calls, then making a HEAD request to the server will print "calling on_get".

In any case, this just means the resource rules need to be added in the correct order. will fix!

```python
from werkzeug import run_simple, Request, Response

from localstack.http import Router, route


@route("/foo", methods=["HEAD"])
def on_head(request, args):
    print("calling on_head")
    return Response("HEAD")


@route("/foo", methods=["GET"])
def on_get(request, args):
    print("calling on_get")
    return Response("GET")


def main():
    router = Router()

    router.add_route_endpoint(on_head)
    router.add_route_endpoint(on_get)

    run_simple("localhost", 5000, Request.application(router.dispatch))


if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
```

